    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nThere is an inconsistency between Lua's `vim.split()` function and Vim's built-in `split()` function when handling empty strings with empty separators.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Run nvim --clean in terminal\n2. Run `:echo split(\"\", \"\",0)` in Vim - prints `[]`\n2. Run `:echo split(\"\", \"\",1)` in Vim - prints `['']`\n3. Run `:=vim.split(\"\", \"\", {trimempty=true})` - prints `{}`\n4. Run `:=vim.split(\"\", \"\", {trimempty=false})` - prints `{}`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nBoth functions should return consistent results. Either:\n- Both return `['']` when `keepempty=1` or `opts={trimempty=false}`\n- Or both return `[]` when `keepempty=0` or `opts={trimempty=true}`\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.12.0-dev-1262+gb756a6165a\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo, it's a Lua problem.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux x86_64\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nalacritty 0.15.1 (0c405d53)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nalacritty\n\n### Installation\n\nbob use nightly",
