            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I don't this this comparison makes sense. `split()` never actually uses an empty string as the separator:\n```\n\t\tMake a |List| out of {string}.  When {pattern} is omitted or\n\t\tempty each white space separated sequence of characters\n\t\tbecomes an item.\n```\nwhile `vim.split()` does.\n\nFor example, `split('abc def', '')` returns `['abc', 'def']`, while `vim.split('abc def', '')` returns `{ \"a\", \"b\", \"c\", \" \", \"d\", \"e\", \"f\" }`.\n\nThe equivalent to `split('', '')` is actually `vim.split('', '%s')`, which does behave consistently with `split('', '')`.",
